				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Note to Commuter: Make Yourself Heard</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Eleanor Randolph			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-04-09T21:27:03+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 9, 2015 5:27 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 9, 2015 5:27 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/note-to-commuter-make-yourself-heard/" data-title="Note to Commuter: Make Yourself Heard" data-description="City leaders are asking for ordinary straphangersâ help convincing Congress to fund improvements to the nationâs transportation infrastructure.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="p1"><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/opinion/9randolphWEB/9randolphWEB-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/opinion/9randolphWEB/9randolphWEB-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/opinion/9randolphWEB/9randolphWEB-blog480.jpg" id="100000003620359" width="480" height="320" alt="Senator Charles Schumer and Mayor Bill de Blasio"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Senator Charles Schumer and Mayor Bill de Blasio</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Pool photo by Michael Appleton</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio joined more than 60 mayors across the country on Thursday morning for a nationwide rally on behalf of the American commuter.Â  Mr. de Blasio, Senator Charles Schumer and other bigwigs actually took the city subway (the R train) to make their point. The well-dressed cluster <a href="//cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/de-blasio-rides-the-subway-a-flight-of-whimsy-with-an-undertone-of-purpose/">startled veteran subway riders</a>Â who are usually interrupted by people begging for money, not beseeching them to contact their members of Congress about the highway trust fund.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The idea is for city politicians of all sorts â Republicans, Democrats, Independents â to start pressuring Congress to renew the nationâs massive transportation act that expires May 31.Â  These city leaders will then try to convince commuters (many of whom are also voters) to remind Washingtonâs politicians (many of whom ride in limousines) that a vital economy depends on a dependable way for all of us to get to work.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">New Yorkers struggle daily on the Metropolitan Transportation Authorityâs subways, trains and buses. They now collect horror stories about long delays and missed engagements. The M.T.A., the nationâs largest transportation network, is also struggling, in the agencyâs case with a five year capital plan that is more than $15 billion short.Â  The state needs to contribute more. The city needs to contribute more. And both Mr. de Blasio and Governor Andrew Cuomo need to come up with a better way to fund the system that serves the most populous 5,000 square mile area in the region.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, the big money will have to come from Congress. President Obamaâs $478 billion transportation bill, which is known as the Grow America Act, would help improve roads, bridges, subways, tunnels, buses and other costly items that keep the nation moving. Â The bill increases a tax on foreign earnings to help pay $317 billion a year for highways and $115 billion a year for transit.Â  This investment wouldÂ not only repair the nationâs infrastructure, it wouldÂ also create jobs. The unions like it. So do most business groups. It should be an easy sell, even for the powers on Capitol Hill.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kathryn Wylde, who heads the Partnership of New York City that includes most of the cityâs top businesses, rode the R train along with the mayor and the senator. It was an act of solidarity, an endorsement from the business community. At least 75 per cent of the countryâs economic output comes from urban centers, she said afterwards, and those centers depend on adequate mass transit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thus, Ms. Wylde said, her appeal to Congress on renewing and fully funding the transportation bill would come down to one theme: âThe whole country is going to suffer if we donât do it.â</p>
